SIMPLE: platform
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Platform
<hw>Plat"form`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Plat</ets>,
a. + <ets>-form</ets>: cf. F. <ets>plateforme</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>A plat; a plan; a sketch; a model; a pattern. Used also
figuratively.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A place laid out after a model.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>lf the <qex>platform</qex> just reflects the order.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Any flat or horizontal surface; especially, one that
is raised above some particular level, as a framework of timber or
boards horizontally joined so as to form a roof, or a raised floor, or
portion of a floor; a landing; a dais; a stage, for speakers,
performers, or workmen; a standing place.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A declaration of the principles upon which a person,
a sect, or a party proposes to stand; a declared policy or system;
<as>as, the Saybrook <ex>platform</ex>; a political
<ex>platform</ex>.</as></def> ⟦ldquo⟧The <xex>platform</xex> of
Geneva.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Hooker.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>A light deck, usually placed in a
section of the hold or over the floor of the magazine. See
<er>Orlop</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Platform car</b></col>, <cd>a railway car without
permanent raised sides or covering; a flat.</cd> -- <col><b>Platform
scale</b></col>, <cd>a weighing machine, with a flat platform on which
objects are weighed.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Platform</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Platform
<hw>Plat"form`</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To place on a
platform.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To form a plan of; to model; to lay out.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Church discipline is <qex>platformed</qex> in the Bible.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Plathelminth</ent>⟦br⟧
